                <head>91. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At his February 25 press conference, President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> was asked about a Tennessee Valley Authority decision
                    to award a contract for a steam turbine to a British firm, and whether the
                    protests this decision had sparked would cause the United Kingdom “to cut back
                    on its recent liberalization of dollar trade.” The President replied that he
                    felt the United States should continue to support free trade. He also noted that
                    he believed the United States was having trouble competing with other
                    manufacturing countries because its costs were too high. “We cannot,” he stated,
                    “continue to increase these costs and have the kind of foreign trade that will
                    make our own country prosperous.” For text of his statement, see <hi
                        rend="italic">American Foreign Policy: Current Documents, 1959</hi>, pages
                    1449–1450.</p>
            </div>
